---
/**
 * ai-evaluation/0001 · Figure 5 — "LLM-as-judge: scale, but biased" (known
 * biases → calibrate vs humans → then trust it). Copied VERBATIM from the source
 * lesson (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup>); an .astro
 * component for the kebab-case SVG reason.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 200"
        role="img"
        aria-label="An LLM judge scales scoring cheaply but carries position, verbosity, and self-preference biases; you must calibrate it against human labels before trusting it to gate a ship."
    >
        <text x="320" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >LLM-as-judge: scale, but biased</text
        >

        <rect
            x="30"
            y="40"
            width="180"
            height="120"
            rx="10"
            fill="#fff7e6"
            stroke="#c2700f"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="120" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="#c2700f"
            >Known biases</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >position (favors 1st)</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >verbosity (favors longer)</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="112" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >self-preference (own family)</text
        >
        <text x="120" y="140" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" font-style="italic" fill="#9a2417"
            >a preference may be an artifact</text
        >

        <line x1="210" y1="100" x2="244" y2="100" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <text x="227" y="93" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#6b675f">calibrate</text>

        <rect
            x="246"
            y="40"
            width="180"
            height="120"
            rx="10"
            fill="#eef0fb"
            stroke="#3d54c9"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="336" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="#3d54c9"
            >Calibrate vs humans</text
        >
        <text x="336" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >measure judge&ndash;human</text
        >
        <text x="336" y="94" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >agreement on a labeled slice</text
        >
        <text x="336" y="114" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >randomize order · force a rubric</text
        >
        <text x="336" y="140" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" font-style="italic" fill="#3d54c9"
            >~80% agreement is illustrative</text
        >

        <line x1="426" y1="100" x2="460" y2="100" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>

        <rect
            x="462"
            y="40"
            width="148"
            height="120"
            rx="10"
            fill="#e9f3ec"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="536" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >Then trust it</text
        >
        <text x="536" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >use as a cheap sensor</text
        >
        <text x="536" y="98" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >to scale scoring</text
        >
        <text x="536" y="118" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >confirm close calls</text
        >
        <text x="536" y="134" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110">with humans</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        A judge is a noisy, cheap sensor that scales human judgment — not a replacement for it. A
        strong judge can reach roughly human-level agreement on some tasks, but that's
        dataset-dependent; calibrate before you let it gate anything.<sup
            ><a href="#s5" id="r5">5</a></sup
        >
    </figcaption>
</figure>
